HEADWORD: Scot
<hw>Scot</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A name for a horse.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scot</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scot
<hw>Scot</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. L. <ets>Skoti</ets>, pl., AS.
<ets>Scotta</ets>, pl. <ets>Skottas</ets>, <ets>Sceottas</ets>.]</ety>
<def>A native or inhabitant of Scotland; a Scotsman, or
Scotchman.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scot</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Scot
<hw>Scot</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Icel. <ets>skot</ets>; or OF.
<ets>escot</ets>, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧cot</ets>, LL. <ets>scottum</ets>,
<ets>scotum</ets>, from a kindred German word; akin to AS.
<ets>scot</ets>, and E. <ets>shot</ets>, <ets>shoot</ets>; cf. AS.
<ets>sce⟦oacute⟧tan</ets> to shoot, to contribute. See <er>Shoot</er>,
and cf. <er>Shot</er>.]</ety> <def>A portion of money assessed or paid;
a tax or contribution; a mulct; a fine; a shot.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>Scot and lot</b></col>, <cd>formerly, a parish assessment
laid on subjects according to their ability.</cd> <mark>[Eng.]</mark>
<au>Cowell.</au> <cd>Now, a phrase for obligations of every kind
regarded collectivelly.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Experienced men of the world know very well that it is best to pay
<qex>scot and lot</qex> as they go along.</q>
<rj><qau>Emerson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

